        "title": "If thread scheduler runs one thread at a time then how does java provide multi-threading?",
        "body": "<p>Below is what I have seen on <a href=\"https://www.javatpoint.com/thread-scheduler-in-java\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">java t point<\/a> about thread scheduler.<\/p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Thread Scheduler in Java<\/p>\n<p>Thread scheduler in java is the part of the JVM that decides which thread should run.<\/p>\n<p>There is no guarantee that which runnable thread will be chosen to run by the thread scheduler.<\/p>\n<p>Only one thread at a time can run in a single process.<\/p>\n<p>The thread scheduler mainly uses preemptive or time slicing scheduling to schedule the threads.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
